{
  "query": "What evidence exists for the effectiveness of different strategies to combat white-nose syndrome in bats?",
  "relevant_summary": "One study in the USA found that a greater number of little brown bats infected with white-nose syndrome survived in hibernation chambers at 4\u00b0C than at 10\u00b0C (1013). The same study also found that infected little brown bats stayed in hibernation for longer in hibernation chambers at 4\u00b0C than at 10\u00b0C (1013). Two studies have evaluated the effects of treating bats with a probiotic bacterium for white-nose syndrome (2008). One randomized, controlled study in Canada found that treating little brown bats with a probiotic at the time of infection increased survival and reduced disease symptoms in a laboratory setting. However, the same study found that bats treated 21 days prior to infection had worse symptoms (2008). A randomized, controlled study in the USA found that treating little brown bats with a probiotic in a mine increased the survival of free-flying bats, but not of caged bats (2008). The same study found that the severity of white-nose syndrome in caged bats was similar to that of untreated bats(2008). There were no studies found that evaluated the effects of culling bats infected with white-nose syndrome on bat populations (1012).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1013",
    "2008",
    "1012"
  ]
}

