{
  "query": "To protect bats from the impacts of mining operations, what actions can be taken during and after mine closure and reclamation?",
  "relevant_summary": "During and after mine closure and reclamation, several actions can be taken to protect bats. One action is to install and maintain gates at mine entrances to restrict public access. Studies have shown varied effects on bat populations; some found fewer bats in mines after gates were installed, while another found that bat activity remained stable or increased at most gated mines (1963). Gate design is a factor, as one study noted that bats abandoned four mines with \u2018ladder\u2019 design gates (1963). These gates can also alter bat behavior, causing them to circle more and enter mines less frequently, and in some cases, bats can collide with the gates (1963). Another action is to maintain the microclimate in closed or abandoned mines. One study found that modifying the microclimate of an abandoned mine by closing a man-made entrance resulted in a greater number of bats hibernating within it (1964). For the action of excluding bats from roosts prior to mine reclamation, no studies were found that evaluated its effects on bat populations (1961).",
